{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492398","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492398"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:27:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:27:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1048"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1048","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1048"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.21,0.59,0.04,0.07,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1048"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90568"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1048","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1048"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1048"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74779"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"3464"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4555"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31078"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90568","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90568"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a single episode of epigastric pain that lasted several hours after a meal before resolving spontaneously. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Abdominal examination is unremarkable with no tenderness or palpable masses. A computed tomography scan of the abdomen is ordered (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["CT-guided biopsy","Endoscopy","MRI scan","Ultrasound","Urea breath test"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe CT scan shows a large, smooth-surfaced, and homogenous mass in the distal stomach, which is highly suggestive of a gastrointestinal stromal tumour (GIST). GISTs are mesenchymal tumours that most commonly occur in the stomach (50-60%) and proximal small intestine (30-35%), though they can occur anywhere along the gastrointestinal tract. Many GISTs are found incidentally, but symptomatic patients typically present with non-specific symptoms such as abdominal pain, nausea, vomiting, or a palpable mass.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step in management for a suspected gastric GIST. This allows direct visualisation of the lesion and the opportunity to perform endoscopic ultrasound-guided biopsy (EUS), which is the preferred method for tissue sampling. Endoscopy can also help exclude other gastric pathologies and assess for mucosal involvement or ulceration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT-guided biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is contraindicated for suspected GISTs due to the high risk of peritoneal seeding and tumour rupture. GISTs are highly friable tumours, and percutaneous approaches can lead to tumour spillage, which significantly worsens prognosis. If tissue diagnosis is needed, it should be obtained via endoscopic ultrasound-guided biopsy or during surgical resection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMRI scan\u003C/strong\u003E would not provide significant additional information in this case. The CT scan has already demonstrated the mass and its relationship to surrounding structures. While MRI may offer better soft tissue contrast in some cases, it is not the next appropriate step when a gastric mass has already been identified on CT.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUltrasound\u003C/strong\u003E is not an appropriate imaging modality for further evaluation of a gastric mass. It is limited by operator dependence, patient body habitus, and the presence of bowel gas. Additionally, it would not provide better characterisation of the mass than the CT scan already performed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrea breath test\u003C/strong\u003E is used to detect \u003Cem\u003EHelicobacter pylori\u003C/em\u003E infection, which is not relevant to the management of a suspected GIST. The well-defined mass seen on CT is not consistent with peptic ulcer disease, making this test inappropriate for the clinical scenario.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Gastrointestinal stromal tumours (GISTs) most commonly occur in the stomach and small intestine and are often found incidentally.","Endoscopy with endoscopic ultrasound-guided biopsy is the preferred diagnostic approach for suspected gastric GISTs.","Percutaneous biopsy is contraindicated for suspected GISTs due to the risk of peritoneal seeding and tumour rupture."],"references":["Vernuccio F, Taibbi A, Picone D, et al. Imaging of gastrointestinal stromal tumors: from diagnosis to evaluation of therapeutic response. Anticancer research. 2016;36(6):2639-48. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27272772/","Parab TM, DeRogatis MJ, Boaz AM, et al. Gastrointestinal stromal tumors: a comprehensive review. Journal of gastrointestinal oncology. 2019;10(1):144. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30788170/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74779"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1048"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18769"}]},"explanation